# Re_Call

Read `AGENTS.md` first. Adam's taste and understanding are the acceptance bar — not generic iOS or UX conventions.

## Before you ship changes

- `./qc.sh` must go green (trust contract). Use `./qc.sh --full` when iOS behavior changed.
- Ontology edits: `ontology/validate.sh` must pass.
- iOS gotchas: read `HANDOFF.md` before touching `ios/ReCall/App/`.

## QC is native-only (web layer retired 2026-06-17)

`./qc.sh` verifies three layers: **engine** (node unit tests + KG→`recommendations.js` compile),
**native build**, and **native device smoke** (XCUITest). The old "Playwright web behavior" and
"web bundle integrity (`data-src-md5`)" checks were **removed** — the app renders no WebView, so
they were permanent false-red. `WebView.swift` and `ios/ReCall/Web/*` are legacy/reference only.
Do not re-add web QC or try to "fix the stale bundle" unless a WebView becomes a runtime surface.

## Layer boundaries (parallel work)

- **Ontology / engine**: `ontology/`, `src/*-engine.js`, `src/recommender-stack.js`, `scripts/build-recommendations.mjs`
- **iOS native**: `ios/ReCall/App/*.swift` only — no WebView restoration
- **Supabase**: `supabase/migrations/`, `src/supabase-*.js`

Do not cross layers in one pass unless the task explicitly requires it.

## Agent behavior

- Phase 1 (judgment): explain trade-offs in plain language before building.
- Phase 2 (execution): plan → edit → run QC → fix failures.
- Never force-unwrap Swift. Never delete completed reminders. Never bundle web artifacts into the iOS target.
